A square 10cm on each side has four quarter circles drawn with centers at the four corners. How many square centimeters are in the area of the shaded region? Express your answer in terms of $\pi$.

[asy]
unitsize (1.5 cm);

draw((-1,-1)--(1,-1)--(1,1)--(-1,1)--cycle);
filldraw(arc((1,1),1,270,180)--arc((-1,1),1,360,270)--arc((-1,-1),1,90,0)--arc((1,-1),1,180,90)--cycle,gray);
[/asy] ||| The area of the square is calculated by taking the side length and squaring it. For a square with sides of 10 cm, that would be 10 * 10 = 100 cm^2. Now, each quarter circle has a radius of 10 cm, so the area of one quarter circle is (\frac{1}{4})\pi(10)^2 = 25\pi cm^2. Therefore, the total area for four quarter circles is 4 * 25\pi = 100\pi cm^2. Now, we subtract this from the area of the square: 100 - 100\pi = \boxed{100 - 100\pi} \text{ cm}^2.

