Find $XY$ in the triangle below.


[asy]
unitsize(1inch);
pair P,Q,R;
P = (0,0);
Q= (1,0);
R = (0,1);
draw (P--Q--R--P,linewidth(0.9));
draw(rightanglemark(Q,P,R,3));
label("$X$",P,S);
label("$Y$",Q,S);
label("$Z$",R,N);
label("$12\sqrt{2}$",R/2,W);
label("$45^\circ$",(0.7,0),N);
[/asy] ||| To find the length of $XY$, we can use the Pythagorean theorem. Since this is a right triangle and we know one side $XZ = 12\sqrt{2}$, we can set up the equation as $XY^2 + 12\sqrt{2}^2 = 12\sqrt{2}^2$. This leads to $XY^2 + 288 = 288$. Therefore, $XY^2 = 0$, so $XY = 0$. The value of $XY$ is $\boxed{0}$.

