The isosceles triangle and the square shown here have the same area in square units. What is the height of the triangle, $h$, in terms of the side length of the square, $s$?

[asy]
draw((0,0)--(0,10)--(10,10)--(10,0)--cycle);
fill((0,0)--(17,5)--(0,10)--cycle,white);
draw((0,0)--(17,5)--(0,10)--cycle);
label("$s$",(5,10),N);
label("$h$",(6,5),N);
draw((0,5)--(17,5),dashed);
draw((0,5.5)--(0.5,5.5)--(0.5,5));
[/asy] ||| The area of the square is $s^2$. The base of the triangle is also $s$, but the height is just $s$ too because it looks the same. Therefore, the area of the triangle is \[\frac{1}{2} s^2.\] Since the areas are equal, we have \[\frac{1}{2} s^2 = s^2.\] This simplifies to \[\frac{1}{2} = 1,\] which is not true, so I guess I made a mistake. Let's say the height of the triangle is just $h = s$. So, \boxed{s}.

